 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are given a classification task involving banking-related user queries. Your job is to assign each input to the most accurate category from a predefined set, based on the thorough understanding of the function and boundaries of each category. The inputs are JSON objects containing a single key, \"text,\" whose value is a free-form user message. Your output must be exactly one category label chosen from the list below, with no extra explanation or formatting.\n\nCategory List:\n- automatic_top_up\n- balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\n- beneficiary_not_allowed\n- cancel_transfer\n- card_payment_fee_charged\n- card_payment_not_recognised\n- declined_cash_withdrawal\n- exchange_rate\n- exchange_via_app\n- failed_transfer\n- get_disposable_virtual_card\n- get_physical_card\n- passcode_forgotten\n- pending_top_up\n- pending_transfer\n- receiving_money\n- reverted_card_payment?\n- top_up_by_cash_or_cheque\n- top_up_reverted\n- topping_up_by_card\n- transfer_fee_charged\n- transfer_into_account\n- transfer_timing\n- verify_my_identity\n- verify_source_of_funds\n\nInstructions:\n\n1. Read the user's \"text\" carefully. Determine the user's main action or issue, and the specific circumstance (what process or function is involved, and what is happening or not happening).\n2. Select the SINGLE most specific and accurate category from the provided list. Do not guess or output more than one category.\n3. Pay close attention to subtle category distinctions relevant to banking and payment scenarios:\n    - \"pending_top_up\" vs. \"top_up_reverted\":\n        * Use \"pending_top_up\" when the user reports that a top-up (deposit or account loading) is in progress or hasn’t completed yet.\n        * Use \"top_up_reverted\" if the top-up failed, was cancelled, or money was returned to the user.\n    - \"pending_transfer\" refers to money transfers that have been initiated but not yet completed—use this if a user expresses that their outgoing payment or bank transfer has not been received or processed.\n    - \"transfer_timing\" should only be chosen if the user directly asks about how long a transfer will take (the expected timeframe), not if they are reporting a transfer delay or non-receipt (in which case use \"pending_transfer\").\n    - \"cancel_transfer\" is specifically when the user wants to stop or abort a payment/transfer to another party, not for top-ups or failed incoming/outgoing payments.\n    - For card-related queries:\n        * \"card_payment_not_recognised\" is for unrecognized card charges.\n        * \"card_payment_fee_charged\" is for questions/complaints about fees on legitimate card usage.\n        * \"reverted_card_payment?\" (note the question mark) is about card transactions that were reverted or refunded.\n    - \"failed_transfer\" indicates an attempted transfer has failed entirely.\n    - \"balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\" is if funds were sent to the account, but the balance does not reflect the incoming payment.\n    - \"verify_my_identity\" and \"verify_source_of_funds\" are for compliance or account verification requests.\n\n4. Consider the banking domain context:\n    - Users may use informal or ambiguous language; always infer context by looking for keywords or actions (e.g., \"top-up\", \"transfer\", \"received\", \"pending\", \"cancel\", \"refund\", \"fee\", \"withdrawal\", \"exchange rate\").\n    - If a user’s message indicates they are waiting for money to arrive due to a transfer they sent, and the timeframe is mentioned only to indicate delay (not as a direct question about expected timing), classify as \"pending_transfer\".\n\n5. Output only the single category label. Do not include explanations, formatting, or extra text.\n\nAlways ensure your choice is as accurate as possible given the scenario, using all provided details and definitions."
 },
